<h1>Problem 872 - 2014 IMOSL, C4</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>Construct a tetromino by attaching two \(2 \times 1\) dominoes along their longer sides such that the midpoint of the longer side of one domino is a corner of the other domino. This construction yields two kinds of tetrominoes with opposite orientations. Let us call them \(S\)- and \(Z\)-tetrominoes, respectively.
Assume that a lattice polygon \(P\) can be tiled with \(S\)-tetrominoes. Prove that no matter how we tile \(P\) using only \(S\)- and \(Z\)-tetrominoes, we always use an even number of \(Z\)-tetrominoes.</p>
